``` java
import com.esotericsoftware.kryo.Kryo;
import com.esotericsoftware.kryo.Serializer;
import com.esotericsoftware.kryo.io.Input;
import com.esotericsoftware.kryo.io.Output;
import com.esotericsoftware.kryo.serializers.DefaultArraySerializers.ByteArraySerializer;
import java.io.ByteArrayOutputStream;
import java.io.IOException;
import org.junit.Test;
import zipkin.Codec;
import zipkin.Span;
import zipkin.TestObjects;

import static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;

public final class KryoTest {

  static final class SpanSerializer extends Serializer<Span> {
    final Codec delegate = Codec.THRIFT;
    final ByteArraySerializer bytesSerializer = new ByteArraySerializer();

    @Override
    public void write(Kryo kryo, Output output, Span span) {
      bytesSerializer.write(kryo, output, delegate.writeSpan(span));
    }

    @Override
    public Span read(Kryo kryo, Input input, Class<Span> type) {
      byte[] bytes = bytesSerializer.read(kryo, input, byte[].class);
      return delegate.readSpan(bytes);
    }
  }

  @Test
  public void spanSandwich() throws IOException {
    Kryo kryo = new Kryo();
    kryo.register(Span.class, new SpanSerializer());

    ByteArrayOutputStream baos = new ByteArrayOutputStream();
    Output output = new Output(baos);

    // let's make a span sandwich
    kryo.writeObject(output, "bread");
    kryo.writeObject(output, TestObjects.TRACE.get(0));
    kryo.writeObject(output, "bread");

    output.flush();
    Input input = new Input(baos.toByteArray());

    assertThat(kryo.readObject(input, String.class))
        .isEqualTo("bread");
    assertThat(kryo.readObject(input, Span.class))
        .isEqualTo(TestObjects.TRACE.get(0));
    assertThat(kryo.readObject(input, String.class))
        .isEqualTo("bread");
  }
}
```

@prat0318 for api design, there's two paths that are repeated
- Zipkin Tracer - Many zipkin apis, including [finagle](https://github.com/twitter/finagle/blob/develop/finagle-core/src/main/scala/com/twitter/finagle/tracing/Trace.scala), [ruby](https://github.com/openzipkin/zipkin-tracer/blob/master/lib/zipkin-tracer/trace.rb) and [javascript](https://github.com/openzipkin/zipkin-js/blob/master/packages/zipkin/src/tracer/index.js) use the same approach. Ex `Trace.record("event")`. These apis only offer zipkin features, so are more straightforward to support in zipkin.
- OpenTracing Span - ex https://github.com/uber/jaeger-client-python is an opentracing api, even using zipkin thrifts, but lacking B3 and zipkin transports. Ex I changed their java client to support zipkin https://github.com/uber/jaeger-client-java/pull/34. OpenTracing is a generic API, but has some features that aren't supported in zipkin/B3 (like arbitrary attachments and baggage).

incidentally, just peeked at a [work-in-progress for GRPC trace propagation](https://github.com/grpc/grpc/pull/7942/files).

They are using 2 64bit fields to capture the 128bit trace id.

```
// A TraceId uniquely represents a single Trace. It is a 128-bit nonce.
message TraceId {
  fixed64 hi = 1;
  fixed64 lo = 2;
}
```

An aside, but they don't share the same span id across RPC calls, so only need to propagate the parent (as opposed to the parent and the current id)

```
// Tracing information that is propagated with RPC's.
message TraceContext {
  // Trace identifer. Must be present.
  TraceId trace_id = 1;
  // ID of parent (client) span. Must be present.
  fixed64 span_id = 2;
  // true if this trace is sampled.
  bool is_sampled = 3;
}
```
